{
  "doc_id": "58735",
  "text": "Ataluren (PTC124) as a production corrector or read-through agent Ataluren is an orally bioavailable agent that has been trialed for use in class I CFTR mutations, which affect around 10 % of patients with cystic fibrosis [CITATION_1] . These so-called 'nonsense' mutations involve a PTC. The PTC results in the interruption of ribosomal translation, resulting in a shortened, unstable and non-functional CFTR protein [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Thought to be similar in function to aminoglycosides, ataluren enables ribosomes to skip this PTC, acting as a production corrector or 'read-through agent' , leading to the formation of functional protein (Fig. 1) . The actual mechanism of action of ataluren has been challenged, however, and the drug has been demonstrated to have some off-target effects on a reporter assay using firefly luciferase activity in drug development [CITATION_4] . Ataluren has also been trialed in Duchenne muscular dystrophy caused by nonsense mutations and has been granted conditional marketing authorization for this indication in the European Union [CITATION_5] .",
